          "body": "Hannah's prayer in 2:1-10 is the most theologically dense passage in the chapter and one of the most significant hymns in the Hebrew Bible. It is not merely gratitude for a child — it is a prophetic manifesto about how God governs history. The song moves from the personal (my horn is exalted, 2:1) to the universal (He will judge the ends of the earth, 2:10), and the trajectory is unmistakable: what God did for Hannah is the pattern of what God does with the world. The bow of the mighty shatters; the feeble are armed with strength (2:4). The full go hungry; the barren give birth to seven (2:5). The Lord kills and raises up; He makes poor and rich (2:6-7). He lifts the needy from the ash heap to seat them with nobles (2:8). The song's climax is explicitly royal and messianic — 'He will give strength to His king and will exalt the horn of His anointed' (2:10). This is the first use of *mashiach* in a royal-eschatological sense in the Former Prophets, anticipating the Davidic monarchy before any king has been anointed in Israel. Mary's Magnificat in Luke 1:46-55 is the New Testament echo of this song, and the structural parallels are not accidental — both women are barren-made-fruitful, both songs announce sovereign reversal, both point beyond the immediate to the coming King."
