          "title": "The theology of reversal — God weighs actions",
          "body": "The governing theological claim of Hannah's song is stated in 2:3: 'The Lord is a God of knowledge, and with Him actions are weighed.' This is not a general truism about divine omniscience — it is the chapter's epistemological ground for the reversals that follow. Because God knows and weighs everything, the mighty cannot ultimately prevail on the basis of perceived strength, and the humble cannot ultimately be forgotten on the basis of perceived weakness. The scales are His, and His assessment is always accurate. The false boasting forbidden in 2:3 is precisely the arrogance of those who act as though their position is self-secured — who do not reckon with a God who sees. This principle finds its most concentrated expression in 2:30: 'Those who honor Me I will honor, and those who despise Me will be lightly esteemed.' D. A. Carson notes that this verse is among the Old Testament's clearest statements that God's covenantal blessings are not unconditional in their application — the promise to Eli's house was real, but it was premised on a walk of honor that had been abandoned. The reversal of 2:30 is not arbitrary; it is the exact reciprocal of Eli's choice."
