          "body": "The anonymous man of God who appears in 2:27 delivers the most formally structured speech in the chapter: a prophetic oracle (*ne'um YHWH*, 2:30) consisting of historical reminder (2:27-28), indictment (2:29), verdict (2:30), sentence (2:31-34), and counter-promise (2:35-36). The historical reminder is intentionally shaming: God reminds Eli that the Aaronic priesthood was a gift of sovereign grace extended in Egypt (2:27-28) — there was no merit, only election. The indictment of 2:29 names Eli specifically: 'you kick at My sacrifice... and honor your sons above Me.' The passive complicity of a father who never removed corrupt sons from office is here treated as active dishonor of God. The sentence that follows is multi-generational: no old man in the house (2:31-32), descendants dying in the prime of life (2:33), Hophni and Phinehas both dying the same day as the confirming sign (2:34). But the oracle does not end in judgment — it ends in promise: 'I will raise up for Myself a faithful priest' (2:35). The 'faithful priest' is debated among commentators: near fulfillment points to Zadok replacing Abiathar (1 Kings 2:27, 35); the 'enduring house' and walking 'before My anointed always' open the oracle to a messianic horizon that the canonical context — and the Christological use of *mashiach* in 2:10 — invites the reader to pursue."
