        "excerpt": "Thus the sin of the young men was very great before the Lord, for the men despised the offering of the Lord.",
        "body": "The transition from Hannah's song to the narrative account of Eli's sons is jarring by design. The song has announced that God weighs actions — now the narrator shows us a specific set of actions being weighed. Hophni and Phinehas are introduced with the crushing label *bene beliyyaal* — sons of worthlessness, sons of Belial (2:12). This is not simply a moral epithet; it is a relational diagnosis: 'they did not know the Lord.' The Hebrew *yada* (know) in its covenantal use means personal, experiential, relational knowledge. These men performed priestly functions for a God they had no living relationship with. They were professionally religious and personally godless.\n\nThe specific abuses described in 2:13-16 are not trivial procedural violations. Leviticus 3:16-17 is unambiguous: 'All fat belongs to the Lord... it is a permanent statute throughout your generations.' The fat was not theirs to demand — it was God's prescribed portion. By insisting on the fat before it was burned (2:15-16), Eli's sons were not merely greedy; they were asserting priority over God at His own altar. When challenged, they threatened force (2:16) — the vocabulary of violent seizure (*chozqah*, 'by force') used for what should have been the most voluntary and grateful of acts. The narrator's verdict in 2:17 is the chapter's simplest and sharpest sentence: 'the men despised the offering of the Lord.' The word *naats* (despise, treat with contempt) is the same word used in 2 Samuel 12:14 when Nathan confronts David. It means to scorn publicly, to treat as having no worth. They despised not the ritual but the One the ritual was addressed to.\n\nThe Levitical context makes the offense precise. The offering system was not a religious ceremony performing a social function — it was the covenant mechanism through which Israel maintained relationship with the holy God. To corrupt the offering was to attack the relationship itself. No wonder the narrator says the sin was 'very great before the Lord' (2:17). The judgment that follows (2:31-34) is not disproportionate; it is exactly proportionate to a contempt that struck at the relational center of Israel's existence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Beliyyaal* (worthlessness, 2:12) — etymology debated: possibly 'without profit/use' (*beli ya'al*) or a place of no return (like Sheol). Used in Judges 19:22 and 20:13 for the most depraved offenders in the tribal narrative. *Naats* (despise/contempt, 2:17) — a strong verb of deliberate scorn, not accidental negligence."
