        "body": "The narrator's editorial technique in 2:18-26 is a masterpiece of theological juxtaposition. He does not separate the portrait of Samuel from the portrait of Eli's sons — he interweaves them, so that the reader sees both simultaneously. Samuel is ministering before the Lord in a linen ephod (2:18) while Eli's sons are lying with women at the tent's entrance (2:22). Samuel's mother faithfully brings him a robe year by year (2:19) while Eli is making himself fat from the stolen offerings (2:29). Samuel grows in favor with the Lord and with men (2:26) while Eli's sons will not listen to their father's voice (2:25). The structure is not accidental — it is the narrative enactment of Hannah's song. Two trajectories run in opposite directions, and the God of knowledge is the one doing the weighing.\n\nEli's rebuke in 2:23-25 is notable for what it contains and what it lacks. His question 'if a man sins against the Lord, who can intercede for him?' (2:25) is formally correct — the Levitical system had no atoning mechanism for deliberate, high-handed sin against God (Numbers 15:30-31; Hebrews 10:26-27). But this theologically accurate observation is delivered by a man who has himself participated in the corruption (2:29) and who takes no disciplinary action. The rebuke is homiletically sound and practically toothless. Eli understood the principle of divine honor but could not bring himself to act on it within his own family. His sons' incorrigibility is then explained by the narrator with a statement that has troubled interpreters across the tradition: 'the Lord desired to put them to death' (2:25). This is not a statement that God caused their sin; it is a statement that their persistent refusal to repent had reached the point of divine judicial confirmation — God was no longer restraining the consequences. Calvin and Edwards both recognized this pattern: God's hardening is always a response to prior human rejection, not its originating cause.\n\nThe Samuel refrain — 'grew before the Lord' (2:21), 'growing in stature and in favor' (2:26) — serves as the narrative's hopeful undertow against the dark current of Eli's failing house. The formula echoes Proverbs 3:4 and anticipates Luke 2:52 directly. The parallel between Samuel and Jesus is typological, not accidental: Luke intends his reader to recognize that the one who grew 'in wisdom and stature and in favor with God and men' is the greater Samuel — the one who is both the faithful priest and the anointed King of whom Hannah sang."
