        "excerpt": "Therefore the Lord God of Israel declares, 'I did indeed say that your house and the house of your father should walk before Me forever'; but now the Lord declares, 'Far be it from Me — for those who honor Me I will honor, and those who despise Me will be lightly esteemed.'",
        "body": "The oracle of the anonymous man of God is the most formally structured speech in the chapter, and 2:30 is its theological heart. The oracle begins with a historical reminder: God revealed Himself to Aaron's house in Egypt (2:27) and chose them from all of Israel's tribes for the priesthood (2:28). The recitation of covenant history before pronouncing judgment is a prophetic pattern (cf. Micah 6:1-5; Jeremiah 2:2-13) — it establishes that the relationship was initiated by grace, not merit, which makes the current contempt more inexcusable, not less.\n\nThe indictment of 2:29 is addressed to Eli, not only to his sons: 'Why do you kick at My sacrifice and at My offering... and honor your sons above Me?' The verb *baat* (kick at) is an image of an animal striking out against its master — an image of contemptuous resistance. Eli's passive complicity — allowing the corruption to continue while personally benefiting from it ('making yourselves fat,' 2:29) — is treated by God as active dishonor. The chapter makes no provision for the 'I didn't do it myself' defense. To honor persons who dishonor God is itself an act of dishonoring God.\n\nThe verdict of 2:30 is the chapter's permanent theological principle: 'those who honor Me I will honor, and those who despise Me will be lightly esteemed.' The promise to Eli's house (to walk before God forever) was real — it was not a lie when spoken. But it was conditioned on a walk of honor that Eli's house had abandoned. Douglas Moo's observation about covenantal conditionality in the NT applies here to the OT as well: God's covenant promises operate within a framework of covenantal faithfulness. The 'forever' of an earlier promise does not override the 'now' of demonstrated contempt. The sentence that follows (2:31-34) is specific, multi-generational, and confirmed by a sign: Hophni and Phinehas will both die on the same day (2:34) — a singular event that will authenticate the entire oracle when it occurs at Aphek (1 Samuel 4:11).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Laken* (therefore, 2:30) — the prophetic hinge word of judgment, identical to the *lakhên* of Isaiah 7:14 and numerous other oracle introductions. *Kavad / qalal* (honor/lightly esteem, 2:30) — the weightiness/lightness antithesis from the Hebrew root for glory; those who treat God's *kavod* (weightiness, glory) as qalal (light, trivial) will themselves become qalal. *Ne'um YHWH* (declares the Lord) — the oracle-formula of prophetic authority."
